text:
Wait a min...Humans are to blame....WTF... Are you on drugs or something..What about Volcano's...come on now..Humans were to blame for Global warming.(But they really had little affect) or none at all. Now acid rain is our fault too... Hahahaaa... what a joke this is...climate change is our fault as well... at least you got something right in the video...how it forms and the damages it causes... hahahaaa

Just to re-cap what Volcano's omit 
By far the most abundant volcanic gas is water vapor, which is harmless.
Carbon dioxide (CO2) trapped in low-lying areas can be lethal to people and animals.
Sulfur dioxide (SO2)  is irritating to eyes, skin and respiratory system.
Hydrogen sulfide (H2S)  is very toxic in high concentrations.
Hydrogen halides (HF, HCl, HBr)   are strong, toxic acids.

Sulfate aerosols promote complex chemical reactions on their surfaces that alter chlorine and nitrogen chemical species in the stratosphere. This effect, together with increased stratospheric chlorine levels from chlorofluorocarbon pollution, generates chlorine monoxide (ClO), which destroys ozone (O3). As the aerosols grow and coagulate, they settle down into the upper troposphere where they serve as nuclei for cirrus clouds and further modify the Earth's radiation balance. Most of the hydrogen chloride (HCl) and hydrogen fluoride (HF) are dissolved in water droplets in the eruption cloud and quickly fall to the ground as acid rain. The injected ash also falls rapidly from the stratosphere; most of it is removed within several days to a few weeks. Finally, explosive volcanic eruptions release the greenhouse gas carbon dioxide and thus provide a deep source of carbon for biogeochemical cycles.

Gas emissions from volcanoes are a natural contributor to acid rain. Volcanic activity releases about 130 to 230 teragrams (145 million to 255 million short tons) of carbon dioxide each year.

But yet Humans are to blame for Acid Rain.

author: Gillan Laureth of Seles
text: It would be nice if we could move away from fossil fuels comoletely. Unfortunately the harvesting, refinement, sale, and consumption of these fuels is a multi-trillion dollar industry and were it to vanish the entire economy would collapse. Hundreds of thousands of people would lose their jobs working at power plants, coal mines, and oil derricks and the businesses they support would fold instantly. It has to be a gradual change over many years if we are to make all power generation clean and green. Until then we push for cleaner energy substitutes and try not to litter and keep car engines running well by changing filters, oil, etc, to ensure your carbon and acid rain footprint is as low as it can be.
